		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Burden decks : gosh darnit to fail or viable possibility?<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.44)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=11641'>Eric "Burden Maste" Charron</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=11641&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> July 26, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Since the start of the Lord of the Rings CCG, no burden oriented deck has proved to be menacing for advanced player.  This is a fact!  But why is that so?  And how can we change that?  Well let start by analyzing the many variant of burden decks there is and what each factions can contribute.<br />
<br />
Nazgul<br />
<br />
A Nazgul twilight deck is probably the first thing that comes to mind when thinking about a burden deck.  The reason why?  Well for starters, very few minions can contribute to corruption.  To my knowledge, only 4 minions qualify: Witch-King Twilight, Ulaire Enquea Twilight, Ulaire otsea and finally the Uruk spy.  The Witch-king and Enquea both can wound the ring-bearer which can transform into burden given the proper circumstances.  Otsea can add burden with blade tips on the ring-bearer and finally the uruk spy will be explain later.  <br />
<br />
Because you cannot rely on minions to corrupt your opponent, and because of the fact that a deck is generally made of more minions that non-minions cards, your options at this point are limited.  You’ve got to choose your non-minions cards wisely.   You can always put fewer minions but you take the chance of not having a minion when you need one.  What is your choice of burden cards then?  First, you have “It wants to be found” which adds a burden spotting a twilight nazgul .  I think this card is well worth the 2 twilight because it does not exert the nazgul and add the burden with no additional conditions needed.  Even 4 or 6 nazguls with 2 or 3 of these cards is enough to be efficient.  Next we have “in the ringwraiths wake”.  This card introduce a very important aspect of “burdening” which is cards that exert the ring-bearer or add a burden if he can’t exert.  The problem with these cards is that it can be countered by your opponent with ease just by healing his ring-bearer (Aragorn KIE, athelas, sanctuary, etc...)so you won’t be able to transform wounds into burden until site 7 (after the 2nd sanctuary) most of the time.  In my opinion, you might as well put cards that add burdens directly; its just plain more simple.  Even “Resistance becomes unbearable” doesn’t help that much for one reason: it exerts the nazgul and leaves it open to archery.  A Witch-King with 1 life at the end of the skirmish can’t wound the ring-bearer you know!<br />
<br />
Now for some little less known facts about burdens and Nazgul.  First Ulaire Enquea.  No not the twilight version, the normal one! Hehe!  Well what people seem to forget when they build a burden deck is that their only goal is to corrupt the ring-bearer by putting as much burden as possible, but they can use the burdens they put to good use.  We all experienced the power of the regular Enquea at least once with his directed archery (well kind of) and putting 5 burdens with a burden deck is not that hard.  Some put ‘’Helpless’’ to negate the burden removal ability of Sam and I say that you might as well put some Enquea to kill him outright since seeing him exhausted is commonplace.  And another fact about Enquea is that is Twilight counterpart is unreliable even in a burden deck: he’s not fierce, he‘s not sure of wounding twice (needs 5 burdens), he’s not sure of winning skirmishes and finally, he’s not cheap at 6 twilight.  So most of the time it&#39;s best to include regular version instead of twilight one.<br />
<br />
Burden oriented ability which are triggered by winning skirmishes leads me to yet another problem.  For your minions to win, you need to include pump cards, and if you add pump cards, well you have less burden cards.  Simple logic.  I think this tactic is a waste of cards in most case.  This is why the twilight Witch-King is always good in any burden deck since he will win many skirmishes without any additional cards.<br />
<br />
There is one last kind of nazgul burden deck that can be made which is what I called a “Wraith-world deck”.  This deck is centered on the card of the same name.  This card is really powerful since it adds 3 burden if you spot the ring-bearer wearing the ring and a twilight nazgul.  So basically you have to build a deck oriented toward making the ring-bearer wear the one ring.  You have a deck like this here on Decktech which is called “Gandalf, Gondor, and corruption?!?!”.  Go take a look because the guy wrote a very good (and long) strategy section.<br />
<br />
Isengard<br />
<br />
The prominent burden card here is without doubt “Worry”.  It reproduce the “In the ringwraith wake” effect but in condition form so it has the same problem.  I have experimented with this card and found that the way you put burden with this card is way too unreliable : first it cost 2, second you need to win a skirmish (which again require pump cards) and third it exert the ring-bearer before adding burden.  Finally there is a lot of condition removal in decks today so run the chance that you’ll take one turn to put a “Worry” on table and the next turn, your opponent discards it with his Bilbo so you have to place another one.  It’s a nice way of putting burden in a typical Uruk-hai deck but it’s not reliable enough to be place in a burden intensive deck.  “Cruel Caradhras” is not even worth mentioning. <br />
<br />
The last expansion came with a very efficient burden card: “Can you protect me from yourself”.  Almost any deck has Aragorn and most of the time, he’s the lead fighter.  The opponent has to choose between adding 2 burdens (not one!) or exhausting his most precious fighter.  And an exhausted Aragorn can’t fire directed arrow no more and he’s open to Ulaire Enquea.  Of course, the card is useless if the opponent has no Aragorn, if he’s already dead or if he’s exhausted but you’ll find out that this is not the case often.<br />
<br />
Last but not least you got the Uruk spy.  If you manage to get the ring-bearer to slip the one ring, this little guy has the possibility of adding up to 3 burdens.  This can be accomplished mainly with “Saruman reach” or nazguls that can wound the ring-bearer.  If you take this road, I suggest concentrating on getting Frodo to slip the one ring and forget about putting burden one at a time.  <br />
<br />
Before I forget, one other option you have is using Isengard orcs.  It is true that they have absolutely no burden cards except those that need Isengard minions but since their main attribute is to exert the fellowship, eventually, Frodo will be exerted too.  It is a way to help your twilight Nazguls to add burden on the ring-bearer.  If you want to see what I mean, check a deck I’ve posted here called “One heavy ring”<br />
<br />
Sauron<br />
<br />
Most Sauron burden deck use conditions like “Thin and stretch” and “desperate defence of the ring” which is susceptible to Sleeps but has proven its efficiency.  You can add to this the new “Gleaming in snow” from Realms of the elves which is in my humble opinion, the easiest way to add burden.  Just watch the ridiculous conditions on this card: spot a man, exert a sauron orc and no twilight cost.  Unfortunately, I cannot elaborate more on a sauron burden deck cause I have never used one or played against one.  Here is a deck that uses both discarding and burden called “The burden of discarding”.<br />
<br />
Moria<br />
<br />
A Burden intensive Moria deck is to my knowledge unheard of at this time.  This isn’t surprising since the Moria burden cards are really weird.  You have “lost to the goblins” and “Must do without hope”.  I think that the second card have some good potential since you are almost assured of putting the Balrog on site 5 so you just hold onto those “Must do without hope” until then.  So for only 3 or 4 copies of that card and the balrog you add generally 2-3 burdens at site 5.  And if you use the common Balrog, The opponent won’t be able to finish him with archery.  This card have other very nice advantages: it cost zero and it works at the maneuver phase.  “Lost to the goblins” also has some potential cause it does not exert an orc, it also cost zero, the condition is not that hard (Opponent ring-bearer must exert or take a wound) and finally, you can add up to 3 burdens!<br />
<br />
Sites<br />
<br />
There aren’t many sites that contribute to burdening so it won’t be long.  First you have the Prancing pony that adds a burden to go search for Aragorn.  I suggest putting it in any burden deck even if you do not have Aragorn to make sure the opponent add this little burden.  I usually play the Trollshaw forest for site 2 to help cycle my fellowship a little bit more.  Site 3… nada!  After that you’ve got the excellent Eregion hills which adds a burden directly, no question asked.  For the other sites, I’d recommend putting a site 8 which gives lots of twilight like Gates of Argonoath or the one where you can spot 5 orcs to stop the fellowship.  Finally, no respectable burden deck must go without the summit of Amon Hen cause this site will generally makes you draw all your remaining cards so you have all you need to add those remaining burden.  Generally speaking, burden decks are real site 9 bombs.  Having a witch-king on site 9 with some other burden cards and the 8 guaranteed twilight is generally more than enough to corrupt the little guy.<br />
<br />
Strategy<br />
<br />
Most burden deck need to go second so the opponent march on their sites.  Since Burden decks are a little rougher to play, you need your fellowship to cycle cards efficiently so you can get the shadow cards you need quickly.  I have used dwarves a lot with my burden decks and found them to be really cooperative since they can cycle their cards efficiently.  Most of their equipment and tales cost zero and they have some good cards for drawing.  I’d also suggest moving 1 site at a time to make sure you recycle your cards constantly.  Most of the time, burden decks aren’t made to run to site 9 anyway, so you might as well play it cool.<br />
<br />
Conclusion<br />
<br />
Buy now you should be bored beyond measure and thrilled to see that title or you kept with me learned a bit I hope.  Anyway, as you saw in this article, there is a lot of way to build a burden decks and there isn’t much burden deck on the streets so the subject is still open to many debates.  I hope this article will get people to start new burden decks especially with the new cards for the last expansion and surprise me.  <br />
<br />
N.B.  If someone ever makes a sauron burden deck with “Gleaming in the snow” I want to see it! (No jokes here)<br />
